having the time to eat right. Back in High School, breakfast and lunch were ready for me at the cafeteria. My michelin starred chef, nurse Zing, economically and ethically raised her own chickens in the back yard of the dorm. Breakfast was "red lye" (lentil soup) , eggs, home ground Yuca porridge, fried tomatoes, fried potatoes, pineapple and sausage. The scene is serialistically written: way-cool Zing, who can devour 4 movies a day, with her nose stuck in an encyclopedia, her fondness for whupping nasty boys' behinds while spreading luncheon meat on home made bread between hands: I see her doing that... Then there's me, sleeping!! You bet I cried because all I wanted to do was run to the cafeteria where my mind was filled with the best school meals I've ever had; grilled fish over herbed rice, chicken loaf & whipped potatoes with gravy, rice 'n peas, ox trotters in surinamese sauce... chapters were and continue filling me with pure ancestral nostalgia.

Walking to school, I'd have an afterschool snack in my pocket: a whole grain sandwich, or healthy cookies (oreo tastes like crack, have to educate their outlawed habit!), or chocolate chip cookie dough that was cooled before eating.
